<h1 class="editorialTeam">Editors in Chief</h1>
<div class="row">
  <div class="col-xs-12 col-md-2">
    <img src="{$baseUrl}/public/osuImages/editorialTeam/beaman.jpg" alt="" class="portrait">
  </div>
  <div class="col-xs-12 col-md-10">
    <h2>Dr. Jason Beaman</h2>
    <p>
      Dr. Jason Beaman graduated medical school from Oklahoma State University Center for Health Sciences.  He then completed two simultaneous residencies in Psychiatry and Family Medicine.
      After residency, Dr. Beaman completed a fellowship in Forensic Psychiatry at Case Western Reserve University in Cleveland, Ohio.  He holds board certification in Family Medicine, Psychiatry and Forensic Psychiatry.  After Fellowship Dr. Beaman completed a Masters Degree in Pharmocology with an emphasis in Forensics at the University of Florida.  He recently obtained a Masters in Public Health from Johns Hopkins University.
      Dr. Beaman currently serves as the Chair of Psychiatry and Behavioral Sciences at Oklahoma State University Center for Health Sciences.  He provides clinical psychiatric consults at OSU Medical Center and performs private forensic evaluations and consulting.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
  <div class="col-xs-12 col-md-2">
    <img src="{$baseUrl}/public/osuImages/editorialTeam/som.jpg" alt="" class="portrait">
  </div>
  <div class="col-xs-12 col-md-10">
    <h2>Dr. Mousumi Som</h2>
    <p>
      Dr. Mo Som graduated medical school from University of North Texas Health Science Center with her doctor of osteopathy as well as a masters in clinical research and education.  She then completed and Internal Medicine Residency at Oklahoma State University Medical Center.
      After residency, Dr. Som stayed on with OSU Center for Health Sciences as assistant program director, and transitioned to program director in 2013.
      Dr. Som currently serves as the Program Director  and Vice Chair of Internal Medicine Oklahoma State University Center for Health Sciences.  She also serves on the board of the National Board of Osteopathic Medical Examiners and the Osteopathic Founders Foundation.

    </p>
  </div>
</div>
<h1 class="editorialTeam">Editorial Team</h1>
<div class="row">
  <div class="col-xs-12 col-md-2">
    <img src="{$baseUrl}/public/osuImages/editorialTeam/allen.jpg" alt="" class="portrait">
  </div>
  <div class="col-xs-12 col-md-10">
    <h2>Dr. Robert Allen</h2>
    <p>
      Born in Tulsa, Oklahoma and lived here until age 5 at which time my family moved to Venezuela for 5 years.  Finished high school in Tulsa and graduated from the University of Tulsa with a B.S. in Zoology.  Completed a PhD degree at Purdue University in West Lafayette, IN and entered a Post-doctoral fellowship at Scripps Clinic and Research Foundation in La Jolla, CA for 3.5 years.

      First job (1981) was with the American Red Cross Regional Blood Center in St. Louis, MO as Assistant Scientific Director over the Blood Services Research program.  Became Scientific Director in 1989.  During the time with the American Red Cross, Dr. Allen became interested in variability in DNA and how that could be used for human identification in disputed family relationships and in criminal investigation.  Dr. Allen began to offer his DNA testing services to law enforcement in 1989 and within 1-2 years was conducting forensic DNA testing for all violent crimes investigated and prosecuted for the St. Louis County Police Department. St. Louis County was one of the early metropolitan areas to exploit the use of forensic DNA testing in prosecuting crime.

      Moved back to Tulsa in 1992 as Director of the Human Identification Laboratory at the H.A. Chapman Institute of Medical Genetics at Children’s Medical Center where he remained until 2001.  In 2001 he became an Associate Professor of Forensic Science with the newly formed Forensic Sciences Program of OSU College of Osteopathic Medicine (which soon became OSU-CHS).  He became the Chairman of the School of Forensic Sciences in 2007.

      Dr. Allen has been very active in the field of identity testing, serving on standard setting and proficiency testing committees with accreditation bodies.  He has published over 80 peer reviewed articles and book chapters dealing with human identification and investigation through the use of molecular technologies.  Current research interests revolve around using molecular technology to estimate elapsed time in estimating the time since death and the time since deposition of biological fluids at crime scenes.  In addition, his lab is trying to identify the underlying genetic causes of sudden unexplained death.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>

