  <div class="col-xs-12 col-md-10">
    <h2>Dr. Randall Davis</h2>
    <p>
      Dr. Davis received his BS in biomedical sciences from Oklahoma State University in 1990. He remained at Oklahoma State University until 1994 when he received a MS in zoology. Then in 1998 he earned a PhD in nutrition from Texas Tech University; thereafter, he trained for six years (1998 to 2004) in pharmacology and neuroscience as a Postdoctoral Research Associate at the Texas Tech University Health Sciences Center. In 2004 Dr. Davis joined the faculty at Oklahoma State University Center for Health Sciences in Tulsa, OK, where he is currently a Professor of Pharmacology and Director of the Biomedical Sciences Graduate Program. He is also a member of the Harold Hamm Diabetes Center. Dr. Davis’s research lab is interested in the role of neuroinflammation and neuroimmune signaling in mood disorders, Parkinson’s disease, Alzheimer’s disease, and obesity. Furthermore, his lab is particularly interested in identifying novel pharmacological strategies to treat these neurological disorders.
    </p>
  </div>
